TI  - Creating social capital on soccer fields: immigrant opportunities and gendered barriers in adult soccer leagues
T2  - JOURNAL OF ETHNIC AND MIGRATION STUDIES
KW  - Soccer
KW  - social capital
KW  - ethnicity
KW  - immigrant incorporation
KW  - gender
KW  - DIVERSITY
KW  - WASHINGTON
KW  - COMMUNITY
KW  - NETWORKS
KW  - AMERICA
KW  - LINKING
KW  - TRUST
KW  - RACE
AB  - This paper examines adult soccer leagues in the Washington D.C. metropolitan area and the level of social capital that exists through participation in these ethnically diverse social groups. Given soccer's global appeal, the communities that form around soccer are distinctly international, and include native-born players, as well as newer, foreign-born community members. In this case study, over 600 soccer players in two different leagues completed online surveys, and 20 players participated in three different focus groups. Results show that both bridging and bonding social capital develops within these communities as over 90% of respondents made new friends and socialised off the field. In addition, 9.5% of respondents reported getting a job or job interview as a result of participation in soccer. The study also uncovered barriers to participation. Women felt less welcome among the more diverse and less regulated pick-up soccer community. While the cost of formal league membership could exclude individuals who were less willing/able to pay for play. In areas experiencing demographic shifts due to increased immigration, however, the support of adult leagues (especially low or no cost ones) could improve trust and reciprocity across racial and ethnic divides.
